{
  "text": "Type B trichothecene mycotoxins are common contaminants of grains and cereals around the world. The presence of these fungal secondary-metabolites raises public-health concerns at both the agriculture and food industry levels. At the top of the trichothecenes list comes deoxynivalenol (DON), the most OPEN ACCESS widely detected mycotoxin in feed and food products in both developed and developing countries. In fact, a recent study showed that DON was by far the leading contaminant in feed ingredients including corn, wheat bran, soybean meal, and dried distillers grains with solubles (DDGS) used in the Chinese market [CITATION_1] . Similarly, a three-year survey of North American grains found that 79% of corn and 76% of wheat/wheat bran samples were contaminated by DON [CITATION_2] . In the southern region of Brazil, DON was detected within the 243-2281 \u03bcg/kg range in almost half (47%) of whole wheat grain samples collected during the 2012 crop season [CITATION_3] . DON levels are also known to vary annually, being significantly affected by weather and farming conditions especially in the years when high prevalence of Fusarium, the major DON producing fungus, is reported [CITATION_4] .",
  "correct_citation": {
    "[CITATION_1]": "15318960",
